## Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by ID from the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID to look up")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search users by name. Returns matching results as JSON.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchUsers(
        [Description("Name or partial name to search for")] string query,
        [Description("Max results to return (1-50)")] int limit = 10,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Searching users: {Query}", query);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(
            $"/users?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(query)}&limit={limit}", cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

## `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: Log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK resolves dependencies **two ways**:

| Style | How it works |
|-------|--------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | The class is instantiated per-request via DI. Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, your own interfaces go in the primary constructor. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services can appear directly as method parameters. The SDK distinguishes them from "user" parameters — only params with `[Description]` appear in the tool schema. |

**Key rule:** `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<T>`, and any DI-registered service are **automatically injected** and never exposed to the LLM. Only `[Description]`-annotated parameters become part of the tool's JSON schema.

In the example above, `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` are injected via the constructor. The LLM only sees `userId`, `query`, and `limit` as callable parameters.
